Advanced (Frameworks & Full-stack Concepts)
5. Create a single-page web app using React
a. To-do list, Weather app, or Calculator
b. Use: React (Hooks, Props, Components)

Let‚Äôs build a React Single Page App step by step.
 I‚Äôll show you a To-Do List App (simplest and most useful). It uses:
‚óè	Components (breaking UI into reusable pieces)

‚óè	Props (passing data between components)

‚óè	Hooks (useState) (to manage state)
1) To-Do List App in React
import React, { useState } from "react";

function TodoApp() {
  // State to store tasks
  const [tasks, setTasks] = useState([]);
  const [newTask, setNewTask] = useState("");

  // Add new task
  const addTask = () => {
    if (newTask.trim() === "") return; // ignore empty tasks
    setTasks([...tasks, { id: Date.now(), text: newTask }]);
    setNewTask(""); // clear input
  };

  // Delete task
  const deleteTask = (id) => {
    setTasks(tasks.filter((task) => task.id !== id));
  };

  return (
    <div style={styles.container}>
      <h2>To-Do List</h2>

      {/* Input and Add Button */}
      <div style={styles.inputContainer}>
        <input
          type="text"
          value={newTask}
          placeholder="Enter a task..."
          onChange={(e) => setNewTask(e.target.value)}
          style={styles.input}
        />
        <button onClick={addTask} style={styles.button}>Add</button>
      </div>

      {/* Task List */}
      <ul style={styles.list}>
        {tasks.map((task) => (
          <li key={task.id} style={styles.listItem}>
            {task.text}
            <button onClick={() => deleteTask(task.id)} style={styles.deleteBtn}>
              X
            </button>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}

// Simple CSS-in-JS styles
const styles = {
  container: { textAlign: "center", marginTop: "50px", fontFamily: "Arial" },
  inputContainer: { marginBottom: "20px" },
  input: { padding: "8px", width: "200px" },
  button: { marginLeft: "10px", padding: "8px 12px", cursor: "pointer" },
  list: { listStyle: "none", padding: 0 },
  listItem: {
    margin: "10px 0",
    padding: "10px",
    background: "#f2f2f2",
    borderRadius: "5px",
    display: "flex",
    justifyContent: "space-between",
    alignItems: "center"
  },
  deleteBtn: {
    background: "red",
    color: "white",
    border: "none",
    borderRadius: "3px",
    padding: "5px",
    cursor: "pointer"
  }
};

export default TodoApp;


 How it Works:
1.	useState manages tasks (tasks) and new input (newTask).

2.	addTask() adds a new task to the list.

3.	deleteTask(id) removes a task by its ID.

4.	Tasks are displayed dynamically using .map().
Example Usage (index.js)
import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom/client";
import TodoApp from "./TodoApp";

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root"));
root.render(<TodoApp />);

1. Software Requirements (Setup for React App)
To run the To-Do List app in React, you need:
üîπ a) Node.js & npm
‚óè	Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment.

‚óè	npm (Node Package Manager) comes with Node.js and is used to install dependencies.

‚óè	 Download from https://nodejs.org (choose LTS version).

Check installation:
node -v
npm -v

________________________________________
üîπ b) Code Editor
‚óè	VS Code (Visual Studio Code) ‚Äì most popular for React development.

‚óè	 Download: https://code.visualstudio.com/

________________________________________
üîπ c) React Setup
You can create a React project using Create React App or Vite (faster).
Using Create React App (simple way):
npx create-react-app todo-app
cd todo-app
npm start

This will start a development server on http://localhost:3000.
________________________________________
üîπ d) Web Browser
‚óè	Chrome, Edge, or Firefox to run and debug your app.


